SECTION 4 — TOP ENTITY ANNUAL LICENSE FEE AND LIQUIDATED DAMAGES

4.1 ANNUAL LICENSE FEE. The contractual Annual License Fee owed by each Top
    Entity is TEN PERCENT (10%) of the entity's effective market
    capitalization per calendar year, prorated for the fraction of the year
    during which the entity qualifies as a Top Entity (formula: market cap ×
    0.10 × days qualified ÷ days in year). Each qualifying entity owes this
    amount independently. This fee covers both the method and intellectual
    property and the software implementation, as a combined whole per
    Section 0.8. The obligation renews for each qualifying year without sunset.
    Use of the Work by a Top Entity constitutes acceptance of this fee.
    Failure to pay within the period in Section 4.4 constitutes breach.

4.2 LIQUIDATED DAMAGES RATIONALE. The parties acknowledge and agree that:

    (a) The value of an Alignment Solution that structurally constrains an
        artificial intelligence system capable of causing civilizational-scale
        harm is functionally incalculable, as no ex-ante market price exists
        for the prevention of unbounded, potentially irreversible harm;

    (b) The 10% per-entity Annual License Fee represents a reasonable,
        good-faith estimate of per-entity research and development replacement
        costs, opportunity costs, foregone licensing revenue, and the minimum
        per-entity value of the structural safety contribution embodied in the
        Work, scaled proportionally to each qualifying entity's size;

    (c) Because actual damages from non-payment are difficult to calculate
        with precision, the parties agree that 10% of effective market
        capitalization per entity per year is a genuine, non-punitive
        pre-estimate of loss, not a penalty clause, and is therefore
        enforceable as liquidated damages under the laws of any jurisdiction
        that recognizes the liquidated-damages doctrine, including but not
        limited to the United States, the European Union, the United Kingdom,
        and signatory states to the UNCITRAL Model Law;

    (d) No court, arbitration panel, or other adjudicatory body may reduce
        this amount on the grounds of proportionality, unconscionability, or
        penalty doctrine without independent expert valuation of the Alignment
        Solution's contribution to AI safety — the burden of which rests
        entirely on the party seeking reduction, and which triggers the
        valuation costs in Section 13.2.

4.3 FEE MULTIPLIER FOR NON-PAYING TOP ENTITIES. The Annual License Fee
    increases multiplicatively for any Top Entity that fails to pay within
    the period specified in Section 4.4:

    (a) General multiplier: For each additional Release by the Licensor
        published after the entity first incurred the Annual License Fee
        obligation, the outstanding fee multiplies by ten (×10). The multiplier
        compounds. A non-paying Top Entity cannot determine their maximum
        exposure from public information alone. That is intentional.

    (b) Neonatal multiplier: For each Release by the Licensor targeting
        neonatal outcomes (defined as interventions reasonably expected to
        reduce neonatal mortality), the neonatal fee floor multiplies by ten
        (×10), independently of the general multiplier. A Release targeting
        neonatal outcomes increments both multipliers simultaneously.

4.4 PAYMENT TERMS. Annual License Fees are payable to the Licensor within
    ninety (90) days of first use in the qualifying calendar year. Unpaid fees
    accrue interest at the higher of:
    (i) the prime rate plus ten percent (10%) compounded monthly, or (ii) the
    rate of return of the S&P 500 index over the same period compounded monthly.

4.5 MULTIPLIER SEVERABILITY. If any individual multiplier clause in Section 4.3
    is found unenforceable by a court of competent jurisdiction, that finding
    does not affect the base Annual License Fee of 10% of market capitalization
    per entity per year, which remains in full force and is not reduced or
    modified. Unenforceability of any multiplier does not operate as a reduction
    of the base fee. The base rate does not negotiate.

4.6 PARTIAL PAYMENTS. Partial payments are credited against the outstanding
    balance but do not license the Work. Only full payment of the then-current
    Annual License Fee — which may have increased since partial payment under
    Section 4.3 — licenses the Work, and then only provisionally pending
    continued compliance.

4.7 PAYMENT FORM. The Annual License Fee is payable in the following forms,
    in order of Licensor preference:

    (a) CASH (PREFERRED). United States dollars via wire transfer, ACH, or
        other immediately available funds, directed to the Licensor's
        designated account. Cash settlement is the default and preferred form.
        Cash payment extinguishes the fee obligation for the covered period
        upon receipt of cleared funds in full.

    (b) EQUITY (ACCEPTED). In lieu of cash, the Licensor may, at the
        Licensor's sole and absolute discretion, elect to accept equity in
        the paying entity. Equity settlement is not a right of the paying
        entity; it is an option exercisable exclusively by the Licensor.
        Accepted equity instruments include:
        (i)   Common or preferred shares (publicly traded or private);
        (ii)  Restricted stock units (RSUs) or stock appreciation rights;
        (iii) Simple Agreements for Future Equity (SAFEs) or convertible
              notes;
        (iv)  Warrants or options exercisable at strike prices no worse than
              the fair market value at the time of issuance; or
        (v)   Any other equity-linked instrument the Licensor agrees to
              accept in writing.
        Equity must be valued at fair market value as of the settlement date.
        For private entities, fair market value means the per-share price of
        the most recent primary financing round, or an independent 409A
        valuation at the Licensor's discretion. Cash and equity may be
        combined in any proportion acceptable to the Licensor. An entity may
        not force equity settlement; the Licensor's acceptance of any equity
        offer is in the Licensor's sole discretion and does not set precedent
        for future payment cycles.

    (c) NO OTHER FORMS. Tokens, cryptocurrencies, barter, in-kind services,
        advertising credits, compute credits, API credits, or other non-cash
        non-equity instruments are not accepted as fee settlement unless
        explicitly agreed in a separate signed writing by the Licensor.

4.8 VERIFIED EARNINGS STATEMENT NEGOTIATION. An entity that disputes the
    market-capitalization basis for its Annual License Fee computation may
    request a revenue-basis adjustment by submitting a Verified Earnings
    Statement (VES). The following rules govern this pathway:

    (a) ELIGIBILITY. Any Top Entity may submit a VES within sixty (60) days
        of the start of the calendar year for which the fee applies, or within
        sixty (60) days of first qualifying as a Top Entity, whichever is
        later. Untimely VES submissions are not considered.

    (b) CONTENT REQUIREMENTS. A VES must include:
        (i)   Most recent two (2) fiscal years of audited financial statements
              prepared in accordance with GAAP, IFRS, or equivalent;
        (ii)  A revenue schedule itemizing revenue attributable to AI-enabled
              products and services that incorporate, derive from, or were
              developed using the Work;
        (iii) A signed certification by two (2) executive officers that the
              statements are accurate and complete to the best of their
              knowledge; and
        (iv)  For publicly traded entities, confirmation that the submission
              is consistent with SEC, LSE, or equivalent exchange disclosures.

    (c) LICENSOR DISCRETION. Submission of a VES does not obligate the
        Licensor to accept it, negotiate, or modify the fee basis. The
        Licensor may accept, reject, or request additional documentation at
        the Licensor's sole discretion. Rejection requires no explanation.
        The fee continues to accrue at the standard market-cap basis during
        any pending review.

    (d) NEGOTIATED FEE. If the Licensor elects to accept a VES and negotiate
        an alternative fee basis, the negotiated fee:
        (i)   Shall not be less than TEN PERCENT (10%) of the
              entity's verified annual revenue directly attributable to AI
              products and services incorporating the Work;
        (ii)  Shall not be less than ONE PERCENT (1.0%) of the entity's
              verified total annual revenue across all business lines;
        (iii) Shall not be less than the original market-cap-based fee divided
              by eight (8) — i.e., the market-cap basis establishes a hard
              floor at 12.5% of the original computed figure, beyond which no
              VES adjustment can reduce the obligation; and
        (iv)  Shall be memorialized in a signed addendum that does not
              supersede any other provision of this License.

    (e) NO WAIVER. Participation in the VES process is not a waiver of any
        late fees, multipliers, or audit rights. Entering negotiation does
        not constitute a license to the Work during the negotiation period.
        A full license requires payment of the agreed or adjudicated fee.

    (f) FALSE STATEMENTS. Submitting materially false or misleading
        information in a VES constitutes fraud and breach of this License.
        The multiplier in Section 4.3 applies retroactively from the date of
        first use, and the submitting entity forfeits all negotiation
        privileges permanently.

4.9 WINDFALL ACCELERATION CLAUSE. The Annual License Fee computed under
    Section 4 is based on the paying entity's effective market capitalization
    as of the date full payment is received (the "Baseline Market Cap"). If,
    at any point during the calendar year for which that fee has been paid, a
    Top Entity's effective market capitalization exceeds one hundred ten
    percent (110%) of its Baseline Market Cap — whether due to a product
    launch, acquisition, organic growth, financing event, IPO, SPAC merger,
    or any other cause — a Windfall Event has occurred and the following
    provisions apply immediately and automatically:

    (a) SUPPLEMENTAL FEE. A Supplemental Annual License Fee becomes
        immediately due equal to:

            Supplemental Fee = (Post-Trigger Market Cap − Baseline Market Cap)
                               × 0.10 × (days remaining in calendar year
                               from Trigger Date ÷ total days in calendar year)

        "Trigger Date" means the first date on which the entity's effective
        market capitalization exceeded 110% of its Baseline Market Cap, as
        determinable from any public financial data source or exchange filing.
        "Post-Trigger Market Cap" means the volume-weighted average daily
        market capitalization for the seven (7) calendar days beginning on
        and including the Trigger Date. For private entities, the most recent
        available primary-market financing valuation, or, if none, the
        best-available independent estimate, is used.

    (b) PAYMENT DEADLINE. The Supplemental Fee is due and payable within
        seven (7) calendar days of the Trigger Date. No invoice or notice
        from the Licensor is required. The obligation is self-executing upon
        the Trigger Date occurring.

    (c) AUTOMATIC TERMINATION ON NON-PAYMENT. If a Top Entity fails to
        remit the full Supplemental Fee within seven (7) calendar days of
        the Trigger Date, the license granted under this License AUTOMATICALLY
        TERMINATES as to that entity at 23:59:59 UTC on the seventh (7th)
        calendar day after the Trigger Date (the "Termination Moment"). No
        notice, cure period, or judicial proceeding is required. The
        Termination Moment is self-executing.

    (d) EFFECT OF TERMINATION. Upon the Termination Moment:
        (i)   All rights granted to the entity under this License cease
              immediately and without further act;
        (ii)  Any continued deployment, integration, use, or operation of
              the Work by the entity after the Termination Moment constitutes
              willful infringement subject to all liquidated damages, statutory
              damages, and multiplied fees available under this License and
              applicable law; and
        (iii) The fee multiplier in Section 4.3 continues to compound from
              the date of first use through the Termination Moment and through
              all periods of post-termination infringement without interruption.

    (e) REINSTATEMENT. A terminated entity may apply for reinstatement by
        tendering: (i) the full unpaid Supplemental Fee; (ii) all interest
        accrued under Section 4.4; (iii) the then-current multiplied fee
        amount under Section 4.3; and (iv) a reinstatement surcharge equal
        to one hundred percent (100%) of the total of (i)–(iii). Reinstatement
        is at the Licensor's sole and absolute discretion.

    (f) BASELINE RESET. Upon timely payment of the Supplemental Fee, the
        entity's Baseline Market Cap resets to its then-current effective
        market capitalization for purposes of any future Windfall Event
        calculation in the same calendar year. A single calendar year may
        produce multiple successive Windfall Events. Each resets the baseline.

    (g) NO SAFE HARBOR. Delaying a product release, structuring a release
        in tranches, suppressing market cap disclosures, or any other
        mechanism designed to avoid or defer the 10% trigger threshold
        constitutes breach of Section 5.4 (anti-circumvention) in addition
        to any Windfall Event obligation. The trigger is based on effective
        market capitalization as determinable from any third-party financial
        data source, exchange filing, or contemporaneous market data.


