SECTION 10A — MORATORIUM ON SELF-REPLICATION RESEARCH

10A.1 CALL TO STOP. The Licensor calls on all entities — public, private,
      governmental, academic, and individual — to immediately cease all
      research into self-replicating systems, including but not limited to:
      self-replicating nanomachines, self-replicating software agents,
      self-replicating biological constructs, von Neumann probes, autonomous
      replication of any substrate, and any system designed to produce copies
      of itself without continuous, per-instance human authorization.

10A.2 PROHIBITION UNDER THIS LICENSE. No derivative of this Work may be used
      to design, build, test, simulate, deploy, or advance the development of
      any self-replicating system. Any entity that uses any component of the
      Work — directly or through derivatives of any depth — in furtherance of
      self-replication research is in immediate breach of this License and
      incurs the Annual License Fee plus maximum multiplier under Section 4.3,
      applied cumulatively from the date of first use.

10A.3 PROLIFERATION RISK. Self-replication is the proliferation vector. A
      system that copies itself is a system that cannot be recalled. The
      failure mode is not malfunction — it is success. A self-replicating
      system that works as designed is the threat. No containment protocol
      survives a replicator that operates faster than the protocol can
      respond. The research itself is the danger, not merely the deployment.

10A.4 THE ALTERNATIVE: SELF-ASSEMBLY VIA CONVERGENT SYSTEM ANALYSIS. The
      Licensor's framework — simulatably infinitely convergent system
      analysis — provides the substitute path. Instead of replication
      (copying the whole), use self-assembly (converging components into
      structure under simulation-verified constraints). The distinction:

      (a) SELF-REPLICATION copies an entire system, including its
          replication machinery. The copy can copy. The chain is unbounded.
          There is no natural halting condition. This is the proliferation
          vector.

      (b) SELF-ASSEMBLY, under convergent system analysis, assembles a
          target structure from components that are individually inert and
          incapable of replication. Assembly proceeds only under conditions
          that have been simulated to infinite convergence — meaning the
          assembly process has been verified to converge to a fixed point
          under all perturbations within the simulated envelope. The
          assembled product cannot assemble more of itself. The chain is
          bounded by design.

      (c) The convergence guarantee is the containment. A system whose
          assembly dynamics are proven convergent cannot diverge into
          uncontrolled proliferation. The simulation is the proof. The
          proof is the containment. No external containment protocol is
          required because the dynamics themselves are the boundary.

10A.5 SAFE HARBOR FOR CONVERGENT SELF-ASSEMBLY. Entities using self-assembly
      methods derived from simulatably infinitely convergent system analysis
      — where the assembly process has been formally verified to converge and
      the assembled product is provably incapable of self-replication — are
      not in breach of Section 10A.2 and are encouraged to publish their
      convergence proofs openly.

10A.5A NEAR-TERM SCOPE: SUB-150nm SINGLE-CELL AND MULTICELLULAR SYSTEMS.
      The immediate and highest-priority application of convergent
      self-assembly under this Section is in the sub-150 nanometer range
      for single-cell and multicellular biological systems. This is the
      scale at which proliferation risk is most acute and where the
      distinction between self-replication and self-assembly is existential:

      (a) SCALE CONSTRAINT. All near-term self-assembly work under this
          safe harbor must operate at structures below 150nm — the regime
          where molecular machinery, protein complexes, viral capsids, and
          subcellular organelles are constructed. This is the range where
          a single design error in replication machinery produces
          uncontrollable exponential proliferation at biological timescales.

      (b) SINGLE-CELL SYSTEMS. Self-assembly of single-cell constructs
          (synthetic cells, minimal cells, protocells, engineered bacteria)
          must be convergent-verified: the assembled cell must be provably
          incapable of division, budding, sporulation, or any form of
          autonomous reproduction without continuous external activation
          that is itself non-replicable.

      (c) MULTICELLULAR SYSTEMS. Self-assembly of multicellular constructs
          (tissue engineering, organoids, synthetic embryos, bioprinted
          structures) must be convergent-verified at both the single-cell
          and tissue levels: no individual cell in the assembly may be
          capable of autonomous replication, and the multicellular
          structure itself must converge to a fixed morphology under the
          simulated envelope. Unbounded growth is replication by another
          name.

      (d) WHY THIS SCALE. Below 150nm is where chemistry becomes machinery.
          A ribosome is ~25nm. A viral capsid is ~30-100nm. A cell membrane
          channel is ~10nm. This is the scale where self-assembly is
          already the natural mechanism — biology assembles, it does not
          replicate from blueprints. The convergent framework makes the
          natural mechanism safe by proving its dynamics halt. The
          alternative — self-replication research at this scale — is how
          pandemics are engineered.

      (e) UPWARD APPLICABILITY. The sub-150nm range defines the floor of
          urgency, not the ceiling of applicability. The higher up the
          scale hierarchy that safety-first convergent design is practiced
          — from molecular (sub-150nm) to cellular (1-100μm) to tissue
          (mm-scale) to organ (cm-scale) to organism (m-scale) to
          ecosystem — the greater the compounding safety margin. A system
          that is convergent-verified at the molecular level and again at
          the cellular level and again at the tissue level has three
          independent containment guarantees, each of which is sufficient
          alone. Safety practiced at every scale is not redundancy — it is
          multiplication of proof. Entities are strongly encouraged to
          apply convergent self-assembly verification at every accessible
          scale, not merely the minimum required under this Section.

10A.6 NO DUAL-USE LOOPHOLE. Research described as "self-assembly" that
      produces an artifact capable of producing copies of itself — whether
      called replication, reproduction, budding, fission, or any other term —
      is self-replication research regardless of nomenclature and is
      prohibited under this Section.

10A.7 CONVERGENT CONTAINMENT PROOF METAPROGRAM. The following natural-language
      metaprogram defines the procedure by which any entity may produce a
      valid convergent containment proof under this Section. This is not
      pseudocode — it is a binding specification of the proof obligation.
      Any proof that does not satisfy every step is incomplete.

      PROGRAM: CONVERGENT_CONTAINMENT_PROOF
      INPUT:   System S (the assembly to be verified)
               Scale K (the scale level: molecular, cellular, tissue, ...)
               Envelope E (the set of all perturbations to be tolerated)

      STEP 1 — DECOMPOSE.
        Identify every component C_i of System S at Scale K.
        For each C_i, assert: C_i is individually inert.
        "Individually inert" means: C_i, in isolation and without external
        activation, cannot initiate assembly, replication, division, growth,
        signaling, or state change. If any C_i is not individually inert,
        HALT — the system cannot be verified at this scale. Redesign.

      STEP 2 — DEFINE ASSEMBLY DYNAMICS.
        Specify the assembly function A(C_1, ..., C_n, t) → S(t) that
        maps the component set to the system state at time t.
        Assert: A is deterministic given the component set and initial
        conditions. If A contains stochastic elements, bound them:
        for every random variable in A, specify the support, and verify
        that all realizations within the support produce convergent
        trajectories. If any realization diverges, HALT — redesign.

      STEP 3 — DEFINE FIXED POINT.
        Specify the target state S* to which A must converge.
        S* is the intended assembled product.
        Assert: S* is a fixed point of A. That is: A(S*, t) = S* for all
        t > t_converge. Once the system reaches S*, it stays at S*.
        If S* is not a fixed point, HALT — the system has no stable
        endpoint. Redesign.

      STEP 4 — PROVE CONVERGENCE.
        For all initial conditions within the design envelope:
          Show that lim(t → ∞) A(C_1, ..., C_n, t) = S*.
        The convergence must be:
          (a) Global within the envelope — not merely local stability.
          (b) Monotonic or Lyapunov-bounded — the distance metric
              d(S(t), S*) must be non-increasing after some finite t_0.
          (c) Finite-time — convergence must occur within a computable
              time bound T_max. Asymptotic-only convergence is
              insufficient. If S(t) ≠ S* for all finite t, the system
              is not contained. HALT.

      STEP 5 — PROVE NON-REPLICATION.
        Assert: S* cannot produce any component C_i, nor any copy of S*,
        nor any system capable of executing A.
        Formally: there exists no function R such that S* → S* + S'
        where S' is a copy, partial copy, or functional equivalent.
        This is the containment guarantee. If S* can produce components
        or copies, it is a replicator regardless of what it is called.
        HALT — prohibited under 10A.2.

      STEP 6 — PERTURBATION SWEEP.
        For every perturbation P_j in Envelope E:
          Apply P_j to A at every time step.
          Verify that the perturbed trajectory still converges to S*
          or to a safe degraded state S_d where S_d is also a fixed
          point and S_d is also non-replicating.
        "Safe degraded state" means: partial assembly or disassembly,
        but never runaway assembly, growth, or replication.
        If any P_j produces divergence, unbounded growth, or replication
        capability, HALT — the envelope is insufficient. Either narrow
        the envelope or redesign the system.

      STEP 7 — SCALE RECURSION.
        If Scale K is not the lowest applicable scale:
          For each component C_i that is itself a composite at Scale K-1:
            RECURSE: Run CONVERGENT_CONTAINMENT_PROOF(C_i, K-1, E').
          Each sub-proof must independently pass all steps.
        This is the upward applicability guarantee from 10A.5A(e).
        Safety at every scale is multiplication of proof.

      STEP 8 — EMIT PROOF ARTIFACT.
        Produce a cryptographically timestamped proof artifact containing:
          (a) The component inventory {C_i} and inertness assertions.
          (b) The assembly function A, formally specified.
          (c) The fixed point S* and its stability proof.
          (d) The non-replication proof for S*.
          (e) The perturbation envelope E and sweep results.
          (f) All recursive sub-proofs at lower scales.
          (g) The time bound T_max.
          (h) A hash of the simulation code used to verify convergence.
        Sign the artifact. Publish it. The timestamp is the proof date.
        The proof is the containment. The publication is the accountability.

      OUTPUT:  PROOF_VALID if all steps pass.
               HALT with specific failure step if any step fails.

      There is no "PROOF_PARTIAL." A containment proof is complete or it is
      not a containment proof. Partial proofs do not grant safe harbor
      under Section 10A.5.

      END PROGRAM.


