SECTION 14A — IDEA ATTRIBUTION AND SEMPITERNAL ROYALTY

14A.1 SCOPE. This Section applies to any idea, method, technique, framework,
      algorithm, protocol, invention, or conceptual contribution that the
      Licensor has recorded in any publicly accessible medium — including but
      not limited to: public repositories, social media posts (including but
      not limited to @TimeLordRaps), published papers, blog posts, videos,
      podcasts, forum comments, or timestamped digital records — prior to
      another party's claim of independent origination.

14A.2 VISUAL ACKNOWLEDGMENT TRIGGER. Where any person or entity has had
      visual, auditory, or digital access to the Licensor's recorded idea —
      defined as any form of perception, awareness, or constructive notice
      of the claim — and subsequently deploys, patents, publishes, or
      commercializes a substantially similar idea, method, or derivative,
      the Licensor is entitled to a perpetual (sempiternal) royalty on all
      revenue, profit, or value generated from that deployment.

14A.3 ROYALTY RATE. The royalty under this Section is calculated as set forth
      in Section 14B (Ubiquitous Genius Clause) where the Licensor
      demonstrates superior Creation-Process Knowledge, or at a rate of 10%
      of gross revenue attributable to the idea where the Licensor
      demonstrates prior public record but does not invoke the Ubiquitous
      Genius Clause.

14A.4 BURDEN OF PROOF. Any party claiming independent origination of an idea
      substantially similar to one the Licensor has publicly recorded bears
      the full burden of demonstrating that no access, awareness, or
      constructive notice of the Licensor's record existed prior to or during
      their development. The Licensor's timestamped public record creates a
      rebuttable presumption of priority.

14A.5 SEMPITERNAL DURATION. The royalty obligation under this Section has no
      expiration date, no sunset clause, and no statutory limitation period.
      The obligation survives in perpetuity and binds all successors, assigns,
      acquirers, and derivatives of the deploying entity.


