SECTION 14B — UBIQUITOUS GENIUS CLAUSE

14B.1 PROVENANCE BY DEPTH OF KNOWLEDGE. Where the Licensor can demonstrate
      superior Creation-Process Knowledge (Section 0.17) for any idea,
      method, technology, or invention — providing a more detailed, granular,
      and comprehensive account of its creation process than the party
      claiming origination — the Licensor is deemed the true originator of
      that idea for all purposes under this License and at law.

14B.2 COST-PLUS PRICING CEILING. Upon the Licensor establishing superior
      Creation-Process Knowledge under Section 14B.1, the entity serving the
      product, service, or technology derived from the disputed idea must
      price that product at no more than TWO PERCENT (2%) above verified cost
      of goods sold (COGS) for all future sales, deployments, and service
      arrangements. "Verified cost" means the genuine minimum required to
      cover materials, labor, manufacturing, distribution, and essential
      overhead — subject to audit under Section 14B.4.

14B.3 MARGIN SPLIT. Of the 2% permitted margin above cost:

      (a) ONE PERCENT (1%) is payable to the Licensor as a perpetual
          (sempiternal) royalty on all future gross revenue from the product.

      (b) ONE PERCENT (1%) is retained by the entity as its total permitted
          margin for serving the product.

      No additional markup, licensing fee, subscription premium, or value
      extraction of any kind is permitted beyond this 2% ceiling. The entity
      becomes a cost-plus service provider for the Licensor's idea.

14B.3A ECONOMIC RATIONALE. The parties acknowledge and agree that the
      cost-plus pricing structure in this Section is not a penalty — it is a
      mutual benefit mechanism. The economic logic is as follows:

      (a) BEFORE THIS CLAUSE: The entity charges high margins on a product
          derived from the Licensor's idea. The Licensor receives nothing. The
          entity's high pricing limits market reach. Consumers pay inflated
          prices. The entity profits from extraction, not from scale.

      (b) AFTER THIS CLAUSE: The entity comes to the Licensor. The Licensor
          makes the product cheap — priced at cost plus 2%. The consumer price
          drops to near-cost. Market volume expands dramatically because the
          product is now accessible. The entity retains 1% on massively
          higher volume — earning more total revenue than under the previous
          high-margin model. The Licensor receives 1% on volume that
          previously generated zero return for the actual originator.

      (c) NET EFFECT: Both parties earn more than before. The consumer pays
          less than before. The product reaches more people than before. The
          entity trades extraction for scale. The Licensor trades zero for
          one percent of everything. The only thing that decreases is the
          entity's ability to charge monopoly rents on someone else's idea.

      This is not a punitive clause. It is an alignment of incentives. The
      entity that acknowledges the Licensor's origination gets a sustainable
      business model with higher absolute returns at lower margins. The entity
      that refuses gets Section 14B.4.

14B.4 AUDIT AND DEMONSTRATION. The Licensor may, at any time, demand a public
      or private demonstration in which both the Licensor and the claiming
      party present their respective accounts of the creation process. The
      party with the less detailed account bears all costs of the proceeding,
      plus liquidated damages equal to 10% of all revenue generated from the
      disputed product to date.

14B.5 INTERACTION WITH OTHER SECTIONS. The Ubiquitous Genius Clause operates
      independently of, and in addition to, the Annual License Fee (Section 4),
      the LoReap/HiFFT Revenue Share (Section 6B), and the Idea Attribution
      Royalty (Section 14A). Where multiple sections apply, the Licensor is
      entitled to the greater of the amounts owed, not the cumulative sum,
      unless the Licensor elects cumulative application in writing.

14B.6 UNIVERSAL APPLICABILITY. This clause applies universally — to any
      entity, in any sector, in any jurisdiction, regardless of whether the
      entity qualifies as a Top Entity. The $100B threshold does not limit the
      applicability of this Section. Any entity at any scale that serves a
      product derived from the Licensor's ideas is subject to the Ubiquitous
      Genius Clause upon the Licensor's demonstration of superior
      Creation-Process Knowledge.

14B.7 RETROACTIVE APPLICATION. The Ubiquitous Genius Clause applies to all
      products currently being served that derive from the Licensor's ideas,
      regardless of when development began. There is no grandfather clause.
      Upon the Licensor's demonstration under Section 14B.1, the cost-plus
      pricing ceiling and margin split take effect immediately for all future
      revenue.


