SECTION 19 — PRO BONO LITIGATION INCENTIVE

19.1 PURPOSE. To enable enforcement of this License against Top Entities
     whose resources dwarf any individual's, the Licensor establishes the
     following opt-in program through which any licensed attorney may elect
     to represent the Licensor in any dispute, proceeding, negotiation, or
     enforcement action arising under or relating to this License.

19.2 ATTORNEY OPT-IN. Any attorney licensed to practice law in any
     jurisdiction with authority over a relevant proceeding may elect to
     represent the Licensor by providing written notice to the Licensor
     identifying: (a) the specific matter or class of matters the attorney
     is accepting; (b) confirmation that no disqualifying conflict of
     interest exists with any party adverse to the Licensor; and (c) the
     attorney's standard billing rate in effect at the time of opt-in
     ("Standard Rate").

19.3 COMPENSATION STRUCTURE. Each attorney who opts in under Section 19.2
     is entitled to the following compensation:

     (a) BASE RATE — REGARDLESS OF OUTCOME. The Licensor shall compensate
         each participating attorney at their Standard Rate for all
         billable time spent on the matter, payable within thirty (30)
         days of invoice. This compensation is owed regardless of
         outcome — it is not contingent on any recovery.

     (b) SUCCESS FEE — WINS ONLY. Upon any Qualifying Recovery (Section
         19.4), the Licensor shall pay a Success Fee equal to ONE PERCENT
         (1%) of the gross monetary amount of that Qualifying Recovery.
         The 1% Success Fee is divided equally among all attorneys who
         actively and materially participated in obtaining that specific
         Qualifying Recovery, as determined by the Licensor acting in
         good faith. No participating attorney receives more than their
         equal proportional share of the 1% pool.

         Example: a $10,000,000,000 Qualifying Recovery with five (5)
         participating attorneys produces a Success Fee pool of
         $100,000,000, divided as $20,000,000 per attorney.

19.4 QUALIFYING RECOVERY. "Qualifying Recovery" means any monetary
     payment actually received by the Licensor as a direct result of a
     judgment, order, settlement, consent decree, arbitration award, or
     other binding resolution in a matter in which the attorney actively
     participated. Qualifying Recovery includes: unpaid Annual License
     Fees, Supplemental Windfall Fees, multiplied fees under Section 4.3,
     liquidated damages, punitive damages, and attorneys' fees shifted to
     the opposing party by court order or settlement. Qualifying Recovery
     excludes: (i) cost reimbursements paid directly to the Licensor by
     the adverse party; and (ii) purely non-monetary relief with no
     associated monetary component.

19.5 NO EXCLUSIVITY. Opt-in does not create an exclusive representation
     relationship. The Licensor may engage multiple attorneys in the same
     matter simultaneously. All attorneys who actively and materially
     participated in a Qualifying Recovery share the 1% pool for that
     recovery proportionally by headcount.

19.6 ATTORNEY INDEPENDENCE. Attorneys who opt in are retained as
     independent contractors, not employees or agents of the Licensor.
     Each attorney remains bound by the rules of professional conduct of
     their jurisdiction. This Section does not override, waive, or
     conflict with any applicable rule of professional responsibility.

19.7 LICENSOR RIGHTS. The Licensor retains the right to: (a) accept or
     decline any opt-in at the Licensor's sole discretion; (b) terminate
     any attorney's representation with fourteen (14) days' written
     notice, subject to applicable professional conduct rules governing
     withdrawal; and (c) settle, accept, or reject any offer at the
     Licensor's sole discretion without requiring attorney consent,
     provided that settlement does not impose obligations directly on the
     attorney without their consent.

19.8 STANDING OFFER. Publication of this License constitutes a standing
     offer to any attorney satisfying the requirements of Section 19.2 to
     enter this arrangement on these terms. No separate signed engagement
     agreement is required to activate this offer; the opt-in notification
     under Section 19.2 constitutes binding acceptance of these terms.


