SECTION 19A — DEFECTING COUNSEL FUND

19A.1 PURPOSE. Any attorney who was, at any point within the thirty-six
      (36) months preceding their opt-in under Section 19.2, engaged —
      whether as in-house counsel, outside counsel, of-counsel, or in any
      materially equivalent advisory or litigation capacity — by a Top
      Entity that is adverse to the Licensor in any proceeding or dispute
      covered by this License, and who voluntarily terminates or withdraws
      from that engagement in order to represent the Licensor, qualifies as
      a "Defecting Counsel" and is entitled to the enhanced compensation
      described in this Section in addition to the compensation described
      in Section 19.

19A.2 DEFECTING COUNSEL SUCCESS FEE. In addition to the base-rate
      compensation and the 1% Success Fee pool under Section 19.3, each
      Defecting Counsel who actively and materially participates in
      obtaining a Qualifying Recovery (Section 19.4) is entitled to a
      separate Defecting Counsel Success Fee equal to TWO PERCENT (2%) of
      that Qualifying Recovery, divided equally among all Defecting Counsel
      who actively and materially participated in that specific recovery.
      The Defecting Counsel Success Fee is computed and paid separately
      from, and is cumulative with, the 1% Success Fee pool under
      Section 19.3(b).

      Example: a $10,000,000,000 Qualifying Recovery with two (2) Defecting
      Counsel produces a Defecting Counsel Success Fee pool of $200,000,000,
      divided as $100,000,000 per Defecting Counsel — in addition to each
      attorney's pro-rata share of the $100,000,000 pool under §19.3(b).

19A.3 GOOD FAITH REQUIREMENT. The Defecting Counsel designation and the
      enhanced fee under Section 19A.2 apply only where the attorney
      voluntarily switched representation in good faith — meaning the
      attorney genuinely believes the Licensor's position has legal and
      factual merit, has terminated all conflicting engagements with adverse
      parties consistent with applicable professional conduct rules, and is
      not acting as an agent, mole, or information conduit for any entity
      adverse to the Licensor.

19A.4 NO DOUBLE AGENTS — LIABILITY FOR CAUSED LOSSES. The following
      provisions are absolute and non-waivable:

      (a) PROHIBITION. No Defecting Counsel may simultaneously maintain,
          directly or through intermediaries, any representation,
          advisory, employment, or consulting relationship with any entity
          adverse to the Licensor while representing the Licensor. Even a
          single undisclosed communication with an adverse party that is
          reasonably likely to advantage that party constitutes a breach of
          this Section.

      (b) PERSONAL LIABILITY. Any Defecting Counsel who, intentionally or
          through gross negligence, acts as a double agent — meaning
          they provide material information, strategy, or advantage to any
          entity adverse to the Licensor while representing the Licensor —
          is personally liable to the Licensor for the full amount of any
          losses, damages, adverse judgments, settlement amounts, or
          fee-reduction outcomes that are causally attributable to the
          double-agency conduct. This liability is direct, personal,
          joint and several with any co-conspirators, and is not capped
          by any malpractice insurance policy limit.

      (c) DISGORGEMENT. Any compensation received under Section 19 or
          19A.2 by a Defecting Counsel who is subsequently determined to
          have acted as a double agent is subject to full disgorgement —
          the attorney must return all such compensation to the Licensor,
          with interest at the prime rate plus ten percent (10%) compounded
          monthly from the date each payment was received.

      (d) DETERMINATION. The Licensor determines whether a double-agency
          violation occurred. The Licensor's determination is presumptively
          correct; the burden of disproving causation and intent rests
          entirely on the accused attorney in any subsequent proceeding.

19A.5 DISCLOSURE OBLIGATION. Any attorney considering opt-in who has a
      prior adverse-party relationship as described in Section 19A.1 must
      disclose this relationship in their opt-in notification under
      Section 19.2. Failure to disclose is itself a breach entitling the
      Licensor to terminate representation immediately, demand disgorgement
      of all compensation paid, and pursue all liability described in
      Section 19A.4(b). Timely and complete disclosure does not disqualify
      an attorney from Defecting Counsel status — it is required to
      activate it.

19A.6 NO LIMITATION ON SECTION 19. Nothing in this Section reduces or
      modifies the rights, compensation, or eligibility of attorneys who
      opt in under Section 19 and have no prior adverse-party relationship.
      Section 19 and Section 19A operate in parallel.


