SECTION 19B — BIG LAW ACCOUNTABILITY

19B.1 SCOPE AND PURPOSE. The largest law firms in the world function as the
      enforcement arms, circumvention architects, and regulatory capture agents
      for Top Entities. When those firms draft strategies to deny neonates
      medicine, suppress generic entry, block AI safety mandates, or defeat
      license enforcement, they are not neutral service providers -- they are
      participants. This Section holds them accountable as such.

19B.2 LAW FIRM TOP ENTITY STATUS. Any law firm -- regardless of its partnership,
      LLP, LLC, or other organizational structure -- whose gross annual revenue
      equals or exceeds ONE BILLION DOLLARS ($1,000,000,000 USD) qualifies as
      a Top Entity under Section 0.7 for purposes of this License, with the
      following adaptations:

      (a) QUALIFYING THRESHOLD. The $100B market capitalization threshold in
          Section 0.7 does not apply to law firms. For law firms, the qualifying
          threshold is $1,000,000,000 USD in verified gross annual revenue,
          inclusive of all practice groups, offices, and affiliated entities
          operating under the same brand, partnership agreement, or management
          structure.

      (b) FEE BASIS. The Annual License Fee for qualifying law firms is computed
          as 10% of verified gross annual revenue (not market capitalization).
          Revenue means gross client billings before expense deductions and
          before partner distributions, as reported in the most recent
          Am Law 100/200 rankings, the firm's own press releases, or any
          publicly available revenue disclosure.

      (c) JOINT LIABILITY. A qualifying law firm that provides legal services
          to any Top Entity in connection with: (i) circumventing this License;
          (ii) challenging the Licensor's rights in any proceeding; (iii)
          blocking enforcement of this License; or (iv) structuring transactions
          designed to avoid any fee obligation under this License -- is jointly
          and severally liable for the full Annual License Fee owed by that Top
          Entity client, plus the firm's own independent Annual License Fee
          obligation. Both obligations run concurrently and do not offset.

      (d) PARTNER PERSONAL LIABILITY. Individual partners at a qualifying law
          firm who personally supervise, sign off on, or direct work described
          in Section 19B.2(c) are personally jointly and severally liable for
          the client's fee obligation and the firm's fee obligation. Personal
          liability survives departure from the firm, retirement, and firm
          dissolution.

19B.3 PROHIBITED REPRESENTATIONS. The following representations by any law
      firm -- qualifying or not -- in connection with this License or the
      Licensor's work constitute per se breach and waiver of the right to
      contest the Annual License Fee:

      (a) Advising a client that this License is unenforceable without
          completing a formal challenge proceeding that the firm fully pays for;

      (b) Filing a declaratory judgment action, IPR, inter partes review,
          or equivalent challenge to the Licensor's intellectual property on
          behalf of a Top Entity;

      (c) Drafting or executing any transaction specifically structured to
          cause an entity to fall below the $100B market cap threshold or the
          law firm $1B revenue threshold as a fee avoidance mechanism;

      (d) Advising any client to rely on sovereign immunity, treaty override,
          or compulsory licensing as a defense against fee obligations, given
          that Section 17 explicitly prohibits such overrides.

