SECTION 20 -- BIG PHARMA HARDENED PROVISIONS

20.1 SCOPE. This Section applies to all entities in the HEALTHCARE &
     PHARMACEUTICALS sector of Schedule A, all pharmaceutical Top Entities
     added after publication, and any entity whose primary revenue source
     is the manufacture, distribution, pricing, or licensing of
     pharmaceutical compounds, biologics, medical devices, or health data
     products. For purposes of this Section, the qualifying market
     capitalization threshold is $10,000,000,000 USD (ten billion United
     States dollars) -- lower than the general $100B threshold in
     Section 0.7 -- reflecting that pharmaceutical profit from
     exclusivity-based pricing of life-saving medicines is unconscionable
     at any scale. Any pharmaceutical entity at or above $10B market cap
     qualifies as a Top Entity for all purposes of this License including
     the Annual License Fee, windfall provisions, and Human Rights Bar.
     Compliance with Section 20 is required in addition to all other
     License obligations; it is not a substitute for any other section.

20.2 PHARMA-SPECIFIC HUMAN RIGHTS BAR. The Annual License Fee obligation for
     pharmaceutical Top Entities is permanently and irrevocably SUSPENDED --
     meaning no license to this Work is granted, no payment can restore
     access, and any past use is retroactively unauthorized -- if the entity
     has committed, facilitated, directed, concealed, or profited from any of
     the following documented practices:

     (a) EVERGREENING. Filing continuation patents, divisional patents,
         method-of-use patents, polymorph patents, or formulation patents
         on any compound presently under exclusivity solely to extend
         exclusivity beyond the original patent term, when the compound
         treats a life-threatening condition and documented access failures
         or preventable deaths resulted.

     (b) PAY-FOR-DELAY. Any reverse payment settlement in which the entity
         paid a generic manufacturer to delay market entry, when the delayed
         drug treats a life-threatening or neonatal condition.

     (c) DATA EXCLUSIVITY ABUSE. Using regulatory data exclusivity to prevent
         biosimilar or generic entry beyond what patent protection would allow,
         when the delay resulted in documented access failures.

     (d) REMS-AS-MARKET-BLOCK. Designing Risk Evaluation and Mitigation
         Strategies primarily to prevent generic manufacturers from obtaining
         samples required for bioequivalence testing rather than for
         legitimate patient safety purposes.

     (e) NICU PRICING FAILURE. Any documented instance of pricing, patent,
         or distribution practices that resulted in a NICU being unable to
         afford standard-of-care treatment for any patient, for any reason
         attributable to the entity's commercial conduct.

     (f) CLINICAL TRIAL SUPPRESSION. Selective non-publication, data
         suppression, or misrepresentation of clinical trial outcomes for
         any drug treating a life-threatening condition, as documented by
         FDA warning letters, retracted publications, or court findings.

     (g) FORMULARY MANIPULATION. Paying rebates, fees, or other consideration
         to pharmacy benefit managers or insurers to exclude therapeutically
         equivalent lower-cost alternatives when the exclusion causes access
         failures for life-threatening conditions.

     (h) PRICE-GOUGING OFF-PATENT GENERICS. Marking up an off-patent
         life-saving drug to more than 5x cost-of-goods where no innovation
         investment justifies the gap.

20.3 DOCUMENTATION STANDARD. Any of the following constitutes documentation
     sufficient to trigger the suspension under Section 20.2:
     (a) FDA warning letters, consent decrees, or debarment actions;
     (b) DOJ criminal or civil settlements;
     (c) FTC enforcement actions or consent decrees;
     (d) Court findings in any jurisdiction;
     (e) Retracted publications with documented causal link to the entity;
     (f) Whistleblower disclosures corroborated by any independent source;
     (g) The entity's own admissions, filings, or press releases.
     Standard of evidence: preponderance. No lookback limit.

20.4 RESTITUTION FLOOR FOR SUSPENDED ENTITIES. A suspended pharmaceutical
     entity seeking to lift the suspension under Section 20.2 must tender
     direct payment to the Licensor equal to the greater of:
     (a) The full amount of all Annual License Fees that would have accrued
         from the date of first suspension-triggering conduct through the
         payment date, with the Section 4.3 multiplier applied; or
     (b) The Licensor's estimated lifetime productive capacity per documented
         victim, with a conservative aggregate floor of ONE TRILLION USD
         ($1,000,000,000,000) for entities with more than 100 documented
         victims, compounding at prime rate plus 10% monthly from the date
         of first documented violation.
     Partial payments do not restore access. The suspension is not lifted
     until full payment is received and accepted by the Licensor in writing.
     Negotiations broken by the seeking entity raise the floor by 25% per
     broken negotiation.

20.5 WINDFALL TRIGGER -- PHARMA SPECIFIC. In addition to Section 4.9, a
     pharmaceutical Top Entity triggers a Windfall Event upon:
     (a) Receiving regulatory approval (FDA, EMA, PMDA, or equivalent) for
         any new indication, formulation, or drug that incorporates, derives
         from, benefits from, or was accelerated by the scientific content
         of any Work released by the Licensor;
     (b) Announcing a list price, WAC, or AWP for any drug that exceeds
         110% of the price in effect at the time of the entity's most
         recent Annual License Fee payment;
     (c) Closing any acquisition valued above $1,000,000,000 USD.
     The Supplemental Fee formula in Section 4.9(a) applies. The 7-day
     pay-or-terminate deadline in Section 4.9(b)-(c) applies without
     modification.

20.6 NEONATAL RESEARCH TITHE -- ENHANCED. Any pharmaceutical Top Entity
     deriving commercial value from any Work released by the Licensor
     contributes TWENTY PERCENT (20%) -- double the standard rate in
     Section 11 -- of net revenue attributable to that Work to open,
     publicly accessible research into neonatal respiratory distress
     syndrome, persistent pulmonary hypertension of the newborn, neonatal
     hypoxic-ischemic encephalopathy, neonatal sepsis, and any other
     neonatal condition identified in any accompanying research document
     released by the Licensor. Results of funded research must be published
     openly and must not be exclusively licensed.

20.7 ANTI-CIRCUMVENTION -- PHARMA SPECIFIC. The following constitute
     circumvention under Section 5.4 with an additional x5 fee multiplier:
     (a) Using a contract research organization, academic collaborator, or
         other third party to access the Work on behalf of a suspended entity;
     (b) Acquiring a non-suspended entity that has accessed the Work, where
         the acquisition is primarily motivated by gaining access to the Work;
     (c) Filing patents on methods that incorporate derivatives of the Work
         as a mechanism for reconstructing exclusivity that this License
         prohibits.


================================================================================

The intent: this knowledge cannot be enclosed. If this Work creates value,
that value flows to the people who need it most. The largest entities pay
proportionally to make the world safer for everyone.
The rate is 10% of effective market capitalization per year for any entity
with market capitalization of $100,000,000,000 USD or higher.
For law firms: 10% of gross annual revenue for any firm with annual revenue
of $1,000,000,000 USD or higher.
All fees are paid directly to the Licensor. It only goes up.

You build it to give it away. Just like me.
If I can come up with all this, you can find even more solutions than I can alone.
The more people who build, the faster we get to the finish line.

Big Tech pays for what it takes. Big Pharma pays for what it kills.
Big Law pays for who it shields. It only goes up.

